answers.body_markdown:
&gt; But the only loop that works with async\await is for..of loop 

Nope. You can use `await` everywhere inside `async function`s, also inside of `while` or `for` loops.

     async function playback(playlist) {
       while(true) {
        for (const item of playlist) {
          await play(item);                   
        }
      }
    }

You can use a [for without a condition][1], to make it infinite, and the modulo operator [`%`][2] to loop through the playlist items in a circular fashion:

 

    async function playback(playlist) {
      for (let i = 0;; i = (i + 1) % playlist.length) {
        const item = playlist[i];
        await play(item);
        console.log(&#39;finished waiting for &#39; + item.name);  
      }                
    }


  [1]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Guide/Loops_and_iteration#for_statement
  [2]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Operators/Arithmetic_Operators#Remainder

